tors-42","page_id":"/docs/integrations/custom-connectors","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/custom-connectors#building-your-own-mcp-server","content":"Write JSON-RPC responses to stdout"},"783":{"id":"/docs/integrations/custom-connectors-43","page_id":"/docs/integrations/custom-connectors","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/custom-connectors#building-your-own-mcp-server","content":"The MCP specification has full details on the protocol, tool definitions, and message formats. There are SDKs available for TypeScript, Python, and other languages that handle the protocol boilerplate."},"784":{"id":"/docs/integrations/custom-connectors-44","page_id":"/docs/integrations/custom-connectors","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/custom-connectors#sharing-connectors","content":"If you build a connector that others might find useful, consider publishing it to npm (for Node.js) or PyPI (for Python). The MCP ecosystem is growing, and community servers are easy to distribute as packages."},"785":{"id":"/docs/integrations/overview","page_id":"/docs/integrations/overview","type":"page","content":"Integrations Overview","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Integrations"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/integrations/overview"},"786":{"id":"/docs/integrations/overview-0","page_id":"/docs/integrations/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/overview","content":"How MCP connectors work in Mate and what they enable."},"787":{"id":"/docs/integrations/overview-1","page_id":"/docs/integrations/overview","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/integrations/overview#what-is-mcp","content":"What is MCP?"},"788":{"id":"/docs/integrations/overview-2","page_id":"/docs/integrations/overview","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/integrations/overview#how-connectors-work-in-mate","content":"How connectors work in Mate"},"789":{"id":"/docs/integrations/overview-3","page_id":"/docs/integrations/overview","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/integrations/overview#what-connectors-enable","content":"What connectors enable"},"790":{"id":"/docs/integrations/overview-4","page_id":"/docs/integrations/overview","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/integrations/overview#transport-types","content":"Transport types"},"791":{"id":"/docs/integrations/overview-5","page_id":"/docs/integrations/overview","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/integrations/overview#next-steps","content":"Next steps"},"792":{"id":"/docs/integrations/overview-6","page_id":"/docs/integrations/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/overview","content":"Mate ships with a full library of integrations built on the &#x2A;*Model Context Protocol (MCP)**. These connectors let your AI agents interact with external services — GitHub, Slack, databases, cloud providers, and more — directly from agent chat."},"793":{"id":"/docs/integrations/overview-7","page_id":"/docs/integrations/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/overview#what-is-mcp","content":"The Model Context Protocol is an open standard for connecting AI assistants to external tools. Each MCP connector runs as a local process that speaks a standardized protocol over stdin/stdout. The connector exposes \"tools\" that the AI agent can call — like creating a GitHub issue, querying a database, or sending a Slack message."},"794":{"id":"/docs/integrations/overview-8","page_id":"/docs/integrations/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/overview#how-connectors-work-in-mate","content":"When you enable a connector in Mate:"},"795":{"id":"/docs/integrations/overview-9","page_id":"/docs/integrations/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/overview#how-connectors-work-in-mate","content":"Mate stores your credentials locally (API keys, tokens) in encrypted storage on your device"},"796":{"id":"/docs/integrations/overview-10","page_id":"/docs/integrations/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/overview#how-connectors-work-in-mate","content":"When you start an agent chat, Mate spawns the connector process and passes it to the CLI as an MCP server"},"797":{"id":"/docs/integrations/overview-11","page_id":"/docs/integrations/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/overview#how-connectors-work-in-mate","content":"The AI agent discovers the connector's tools and can call them during the conversation"},"798":{"id":"/docs/integrations/overview-12","page_id":"/docs/integrations/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/overview#how-connectors-work-in-mate","content":"The connector process runs locally on your machine — credentials never leave your device"},"799":{"id":"/docs/integrations/overview-13","page_id":"/docs/integrations/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/overview#how-connectors-work-in-mate","content":"Mate bundles its own Node.js runtime, so most connectors work out of the box without you needing to install Node.js separately. The bundled runtime handles `npx` commands that connectors use to start."},"800":{"id":"/docs/integrations/overview-14","page_id":"/docs/integrations/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/overview#what-connectors-enable","content":"With connectors, your AI agent can:"},"801":{"id":"/docs/integrations/overview-15","page_id":"/docs/integrations/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/overview#what-connectors-enable","content":"**Read and write code** on GitHub, GitLab, or Bitbucket"},"802":{"id":"/docs/integrations/overview-16","page_id":"/docs/integrations/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/overview#what-connectors-enable","content":"**Manage projects** in Linear, Jira, Asana, or Trello"},"803":{"id":"/docs/integrations/overview-17","page_id":"/docs/integrations/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/overview#what-connectors-enable","content":"**Query databases** like Postgres, MySQL, MongoDB, or Redis"},"804":{"id":"/docs/integrations/overview-18","page_id":"/docs/integrations/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/overview#what-connectors-enable","content":"**Search the web** via Brave Search, Exa, or Tavily"},"805":{"id":"/docs/integrations/overview-19","page_id":"/docs/integrations/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/overview#what-connectors-enable","content":"**Send messages** on Slack, Discord, or Telegram"},"806":{"id":"/docs/integrations/overview-20","page_id":"/docs/integrations/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/overview#what-connectors-enable","content":"**Manage infrastructure** on AWS, Cloudflare, Vercel, or Kubernetes"},"807":{"id":"/docs/integrations/overview-21","page_id":"/docs/integrations/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/overview#what-connectors-enable","content":"**Generate images** with DALL-E, Stable Diffusion, or fal.ai"},"808":{"id":"/docs/integrations/overview-22","page_id":"/docs/integrations/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/overview#what-connectors-enable","content":"And much more — see the full connector list"},"809":{"id":"/docs/integrations/overview-23","page_id":"/docs/integrations/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/overview#transport-types","content":"Most connectors use **stdio** transport — Mate spawns a local process and communicates over stdin/stdout. A few built-in connectors (like Mate Canvas) are handled directly by the app without spawning a separate process."},"810":{"id":"/docs/integrations/overview-24","page_id":"/docs/integrations/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/overview#next-steps","content":"Set up a connector — step-by-step guide"},"811":{"id":"/docs/integrations/overview-25","page_id":"/docs/integrations/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/overview#next-steps","content":"Browse all connectors — full list by category"},"812":{"id":"/docs/integrations/overview-26","page_id":"/docs/integrations/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/overview#next-steps","content":"Claude Code integration — detailed guide for the most popular CLI"},"813":{"id":"/docs/integrations/overview-27","page_id":"/docs/integrations/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/overview#next-steps","content":"Custom connectors — add your own MCP servers"},"814":{"id":"/docs/integrations/skills","page_id":"/docs/integrations/skills","type":"page","content":"Skills","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Integrations"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/integrations/skills"},"815":{"id":"/docs/integrations/skills-0","page_id":"/docs/integrations/skills","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/skills","content":"Extend your AI agents with installable skills."},"816":{"id":"/docs/integrations/skills-1","page_id":"/docs/integrations/skills","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/integrations/skills#how-skills-work","content":"How skills work"},"817":{"id":"/docs/integrations/skills-2","page_id":"/docs/integrations/skills","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/integrations/skills#browsing-the-marketplace","content":"Browsing the marketplace"},"818":{"id":"/docs/integrations/skills-3","page_id":"/docs/integrations/skills","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/integrations/skills#open-settings","content":"Open Settings"},"819":{"id":"/docs/integrations/skills-4","page_id":"/docs/integrations/skills","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/integrations/skills#navigate-to-skills","content":"Navigate to Skills"},"820":{"id":"/docs/integrations/skills-5","page_id":"/docs/integrations/skills","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/integrations/skills#browse-and-preview","content":"Browse and preview"},"821":{"id":"/docs/integrations/skills-6","page_id":"/docs/integrations/skills","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/integrations/skills#install","content":"Install"},"822":{"id":"/docs/integrations/skills-7","page_id":"/docs/integrations/skills","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/integrations/skills#using-skills-in-chat","content":"Using skills in chat"},"823":{"id":"/docs/integrations/skills-8","page_id":"/docs/integrations/skills","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/integrations/skills#skill-structure","content":"Skill structure"},"824":{"id":"/docs/integrations/skills-9","page_id":"/docs/integrations/skills","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/integrations/skills#managing-installed-skills","content":"Managing installed skills"},"825":{"id":"/docs/integrations/skills-10","page_id":"/docs/integrations/skills","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/integrations/skills#custom-skills","content":"Custom skills"},"826":{"id":"/docs/integrations/skills-11","page_id":"/docs/integrations/skills","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/skills","content":"Skills are reusable prompt templates and commands that you install into your AI coding CLIs. They add slash commands, specialized behaviors, and domain-specific knowledge to your agent chat sessions — like plugins for your AI assistant."},"827":{"id":"/docs/integrations/skills-12","page_id":"/docs/integrations/skills","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/skills","content":"For example, a \"code review\" skill might add a `/review` command that instructs the agent to follow a specific review checklist. A \"testing\" skill might add `/test-spec` that generates tests from a specification file. Skills encode best practices into repeatable, shareable commands."},"828":{"id":"/docs/integrations/skills-13","page_id":"/docs/integrations/skills","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/skills#how-skills-work","content":"When you install a skill, Mate places it in the appropriate directory for each CLI:"},"829":{"id":"/docs/integrations/skills-14","page_id":"/docs/integrations/skills","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/skills#how-skills-work","content":"CLI"},"830":{"id":"/docs/integrations/skills-15","page_id":"/docs/integrations/skills","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/skills#how-skills-work","content":"Skill directory"},"831":{"id":"/docs/integrations/skills-16","page_id":"/docs/integrations/skills","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/skills#how-skills-work","content":"Claude Code"},"832":{"id":"/docs/integrations/skills-17","page_id":"/docs/integrations/skills","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/skills#how-skills-work","content":"`.claude/skills/`"},"833":{"id":"/docs/integrations/skills-18","page_id":"/docs/integrations/skills","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/skills#how-skills-work","content":"Codex"},"834":{"id":"/docs/integrations/skills-19","page_id":"/docs/integrations/skills","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/skills#how-skills-work","content":"`.codex/skills/`"},"835":{"id":"/docs/integrations/skills-20","page_id":"/docs/integrations/skills","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/skills#how-skills-work","content":"Copilot"},"836":{"id":"/docs/integrations/skills-21","page_id":"/docs/integrations/skills","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/skills#how-skills-work","content":"`.copilot/skills/`"},"837":{"id":"/docs/integrations/skills-22","page_id":"/docs/integrations/skills","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/skills#how-skills-work","content":"Shared"},"838":{"id":"/docs/integrations/skills-23","page_id":"/docs/integrations/skills","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/skills#how-skills-work","content":"`.mate/skills/`"},"839":{"id":"/docs/integrations/skills-24","page_id":"/docs/integrations/skills","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/skills#how-skills-work","content":"Skills installed through Mate are symlinked across CLI directories, so a single skill works with all your agents without duplication. Install it once, use it everywhere."},"840":{"id":"/docs/integrations/skills-25","page_id":"/docs/integrations/skills","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/skills#how-skills-work","content":"Each skill is a markdown file that contains the prompt template and metadata the CLI uses to register it as a slash command."},"841":{"id":"/docs/integrations/skills-26","page_id":"/docs/integrations/skills","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/skills#open-settings","content":"Go to the **Settings** tab in Mate."},"842":{"id":"/docs/integrations/skills-27","page_id":"/docs/integrations/skills","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/skills#navigate-to-skills","content":"Find the **Skills** section. This shows the marketplace — a browsable list of available skills organized by category."},"843":{"id":"/docs/integrations/skills-28","page_id":"/docs/integrations/skills","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/skills#browse-and-preview","content":"Each skill shows its name, description, and what slash commands it adds. You can preview the full prompt template before installing."},"844":{"id":"/docs/integrations/skills-29","page_id":"/docs/integrations/skills","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/skills#install","content":"Tap **Install** on any skill. Mate downloads it and symlinks it into the appropriate CLI directories. The skill is immediately available in your next agent chat session."},"845":{"id":"/docs/integrations/skills-30","page_id":"/docs/integrations/skills","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/skills#using-skills-in-chat","content":"Once installed, skills appear as slash commands in agent chat. Type `/` in the composer to see available commands. Select one to invoke the skill — the prompt template is sent to the agent, which follows its instructions."},"846":{"id":"/docs/integrations/skills-31","page_id":"/docs/integrations/skills","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/skills#using-skills-in-chat","content":"Some skills are fire-and-forget (run a single task), while others are interactive (the agent asks follow-up questions based on the skill's template)."},"847":{"id":"/docs/integrations/skills-32","page_id":"/docs/integrations/skills","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/skills#skill-structure","content":"A skill is a markdown file with frontmatter metadata:"},"848":{"id":"/docs/integrations/skills-33","page_id":"/docs/integrations/skills","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/skills#skill-structure","content":"The CLI reads the frontmatter to register the slash command, and uses the body as the prompt template when invoked."},"849":{"id":"/docs/integrations/skills-34","page_id":"/docs/integrations/skills","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/skills#managing-installed-skills","content":"In the Skills section of Settings, you can see all installed skills and:"},"850":{"id":"/docs/integrations/skills-35","page_id":"/docs/integrations/skills","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/skills#managing-installed-skills","content":"**Uninstall** a skill to remove it from all CLI directories"},"851":{"id":"/docs/integrations/skills-36","page_id":"/docs/integrations/skills","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/skills#managing-installed-skills","content":"**Update** a skill if a newer version is available in the marketplace"},"852":{"id":"/docs/integrations/skills-37","page_id":"/docs/integrations/skills","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/skills#managing-installed-skills","content":"**View details** to see the full prompt template"},"853":{"id":"/docs/integrations/skills-38","page_id":"/docs/integrations/skills","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/skills#custom-skills","content":"You can create your own skills by placing markdown files directly in `.mate/skills/` or the CLI-specific skill directories. Custom skills follow the same format as marketplace skills and appear alongside them in the slash command list."},"854":{"id":"/docs/integrations/skills-39","page_id":"/docs/integrations/skills","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/integrations/skills#custom-skills","content":"This is useful for team-specific workflows — write a skill once, share the file, and everyone on the team gets the same commands."},"855":{"id":"/docs/reference/keyboard-shortcuts","page_id":"/docs/reference/keyboard-shortcuts","type":"page","content":"Keyboard Shortcuts","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Reference"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/keyboard-shortcuts"},"856":{"id":"/docs/reference/keyboard-shortcuts-0","page_id":"/docs/reference/keyboard-shortcuts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/keyboard-shortcuts","content":"Common keyboard shortcuts for Mate on desktop."},"857":{"id":"/docs/reference/keyboard-shortcuts-1","page_id":"/docs/reference/keyboard-shortcuts","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/keyboard-shortcuts#general","content":"General"},"858":{"id":"/docs/reference/keyboard-shortcuts-2","page_id":"/docs/reference/keyboard-shortcuts","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/keyboard-shortcuts#terminal","content":"Terminal"},"859":{"id":"/docs/reference/keyboard-shortcuts-3","page_id":"/docs/reference/keyboard-shortcuts","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/keyboard-shortcuts#editor--ide","content":"Editor / IDE"},"860":{"id":"/docs/reference/keyboard-shortcuts-4","page_id":"/docs/reference/keyboard-shortcuts","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/keyboard-shortcuts#agent-chat","content":"Agent Chat"},"861":{"id":"/docs/reference/keyboard-shortcuts-5","page_id":"/docs/reference/keyboard-shortcuts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/keyboard-shortcuts","content":"These shortcuts work on macOS. On Windows and Linux, replace **Cmd** with **Ctrl**."},"862":{"id":"/docs/reference/keyboard-shortcuts-6","page_id":"/docs/reference/keyboard-shortcuts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/keyboard-shortcuts#general","content":"Action"},"863":{"id":"/docs/